### Membership changes

The early years of the U.S. Congress were characterized by a dynamic, almost improvisational, approach to its composition. Resignations, new state admissions, and the occasional contested election meant that the legislative body was in a constant state of flux. As previously noted, formal political parties had not yet solidified, so members are informally categorized into factions based on their voting records and general political leanings. This period also marked the first representation for the newly admitted states of [Vermont](/Vermont) and [Kentucky](/Kentucky), significantly altering the demographic and political balance of the Congress.

#### Senate

The [Senate](/United_States_Senate) experienced a fair share of shifts during the [2nd Congress](/2nd_United_States_Congress). There were three instances of resignations, one seat that remained vacant due to legislative inaction, and the addition of four new seats resulting from the admission of [Vermont](/Vermont) and [Kentucky](/Kentucky). This activity ultimately led to a net gain of four seats for the Anti-Administration faction in the [Senate](/United_United_States_Senate), reflecting the evolving political sentiments across the states.

